        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
            <h3>How do I extract sales tax from a final inclusive receipt?</h3>
            <p>If you have a receipt for $100 that already includes a 5% tax, do NOT subtract 5%. Instead, divide the final total by 1.05 (which is 1 + the decimal rate). $100 / 1.05 = $95.23 base price. The difference ($4.77) is your tax.</p>
            
            <h3>Are all items taxed at the same percentage?</h3>
            <p>No. Regions often exempt specific essentials like un-prepared groceries, prescription medications, or clothing under a certain price. Always verify your local regional tax codes.</p>
            
            <h3>Is sales tax the same as Value Added Tax (VAT)?</h3>
            <p>While mathematically similar for consumers, they differ fundamentally for businesses. Sales tax is only collected at the final retail point of sale. VAT is collected at every single stage of the supply chain production.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Knowing exactly how to calculate sales tax empowers consumers to budget accurately and protects small business owners from devastating accounting errors during tax season. By mastering the core formula, properly ordering discounts before taxes, and leveraging digital tools to extract inclusive taxes safely, you gain complete control over your retail mathematics.</p>
